statement.p:
Notice how Rule assumes you have one side written as N^{x} with nothing else in front (no coefficient). The left side of our equation has a coefficient of 3 in front of the exponential
3(2.83)^{x}
The constant 3 is keeping us from using Rule. That constant either has to be moved or we have to use another rule (if there is one that applies).

remark.p:
A note about solving. In the two algebra examples we were able to find exact solutions:
x= \frac{\ln \big( \frac{15}{3} \big)}{\ln(2.83)}
is exact.

statement.p:
The word continuous is telling us to use base e. Therefore we can write the formula for decay as
Ae^{kt}
where k is the continuous decay constant k=. This value is negative because we are told the 21 \% is a decrease.

A discrete model looks like

  Ab^{t}

where in our case b is the annual growth factor and A represents the initial size of the population which we are not given.

A continuous model would be

  Ae^{kt}

where k is the continuous growth constant and A still represents the initial amount.

These models must be equal because they are describing the same population. Therefore
A(b)^{t}=A(e^{k})^{t}
Notice what is the same on each side and what is different.

We can write a formula that says,
Start with some initial amount, C, and multiply by 0.5 every  minutes.

  C(0.5)^{\frac{t}{}}

Notice we can rewrite our formula to show the per minute growth factor
C(0.5)^\frac{t}{}=C(0.5^\frac{1}{})^{t}
where
b=0.5^\frac{1}{}
b \approx (round to 3 decimal places)

